 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · The Laws of Indices",
   "html": "<p>For any positive real $a,b$ and any real numbers $m,n$:</p><ol><li>$a^m \\cdot a^n = a^{m+n}$</li><li>$\\dfrac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}$</li><li>$(a^m)^n = a^{mn}$</li><li>$(ab)^n = a^n b^n$</li><li>$a^0 = 1$ (for $a\\ne 0$)</li><li>$a^{-n} = \\dfrac{1}{a^n}$</li><li>$a^{1/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a}$ and $a^{m/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a^m}$</li></ol>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Simplify $2^5 \\cdot 2^{-2}$.",
     "a": "$2^{5+(-2)} = 2^3 = 8$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Simplify $(3^2)^3$.",
     "a": "$3^{2\\cdot 3} = 3^6 = 729$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Fractional & Negative Indices",
   "html": "<p>A fractional index means a root: $a^{m/n} = (\\sqrt[n]{a})^m$. A negative index means reciprocal: $a^{-n} = 1/a^n$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Evaluate $27^{2/3}$.",
     "a": "$27^{2/3} = (\\sqrt[3]{27})^2 = 3^2 = 9$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Evaluate $16^{-3/4}$.",
     "a": "$16^{-3/4} = \\dfrac{1}{16^{3/4}} = \\dfrac{1}{(\\sqrt[4]{16})^3} = \\dfrac{1}{2^3} = \\dfrac{1}{8}$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Exponential Equations",
   "html": "<p>If both sides can be written with the <b>same base</b>, equate the exponents.</p>$$a^{f(x)} = a^{g(x)} \\Rightarrow f(x)=g(x)$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Solve $2^{x+1} = 32$.",
     "a": "$32 = 2^5$, so $x+1=5 \\Rightarrow x = 4$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Solve $9^x = 27$.",
     "a": "$9^x = 3^{2x}$ and $27 = 3^3$, so $2x = 3 \\Rightarrow x = 3/2$."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
